# Versioning and changelog

Every push (top-level agent or Scenario A sub-agent) bumps [SemVer](https://semver.org) and appends a detailed entry to `CHANGELOG.md` ([Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com) format). Commits use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org). Applies in both `MODE: Cloud` and `MODE: Local`.

## Authoritative artifact

- `CHANGELOG.md` at the **repo root**, in [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com) format.
- Repo-root `VERSION` (plain text, single line) **if it already exists** — kept in sync with the latest CHANGELOG entry.
- Language-specific version fields **if any of these files exist** — kept in sync at the same bump:
  - `package.json` → `version`
  - `Cargo.toml` → `[package].version`
  - `pyproject.toml` → `[project].version` or `[tool.poetry].version`
  - `*.csproj` → `<Version>` or `<VersionPrefix>`

`CHANGELOG.md` is canonical: if the language version field disagrees, fix the language field.

## Initialization (first time the repo lacks a CHANGELOG)

1. Infer the **starting version** in this priority order; stop at the first hit:
   1. Language-specific version metadata (priority order: `package.json#version`, `Cargo.toml#package.version`, `pyproject.toml#project.version` or `tool.poetry.version`, `*.csproj#Version` or `VersionPrefix`).
   2. Repo-root `VERSION` file, if it parses as SemVer.
   3. Latest annotated git tag matching `^v?\d+\.\d+\.\d+$` (`git tag -l --sort=-v:refname | head -n1`).
   4. An existing `CHANGELOG.md` written in any other format whose top entry contains a SemVer-shaped string (regex `\b\d+\.\d+\.\d+\b`).
   5. Fallback baseline: `0.0.0`.
2. The **first push under this rule bumps that starting version normally** (default `PATCH`; per the bump rules below). If the inferred start was the `0.0.0` fallback, the first entry becomes `0.1.0` (treated as a `MINOR` from `0.0.0` — this signals "first tracked release").
3. Create `CHANGELOG.md` from the template at `templates/CHANGELOG-initial.md` in this rules pack (or write the same structure inline).
4. **Do not fabricate retroactive entries for past commits.** Start the changelog from this push forward. If the repo already had a `CHANGELOG.md` in another format, leave the old entries untouched below the new Keep a Changelog header.

## Version bump rules — MUST

For each push, bump exactly one part of `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`. Default = `PATCH`. Bump higher only with an explicit reason:

| Bump | When |
|------|------|
| `PATCH` (default) | Bug fixes, docs, internal refactors, test changes, CI changes, dependency bumps with no behavior change. |
| `MINOR` | New feature, new option, new env var, new public API surface — all backward-compatible. |
| `MAJOR` | Removed/renamed public API, behavior changes that break existing users, product repositioning. |

When bumping `MINOR` or `MAJOR`, the `CHANGELOG.md` entry **must** include a `Bump reason: <one line>` directly under the version heading.

## Changelog entry — MUST

Every push appends exactly one entry. Top of `CHANGELOG.md` is `[Unreleased]` (kept empty between releases) followed by the new dated entry above older ones.

Required structure for each entry (header + one-paragraph summary + applicable subsections):

```
## [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD

<one-paragraph summary>

### Added | Changed | Fixed | Removed   (only sections that apply; omit empty ones)
### Breaking                              (MAJOR only — list breaks + migration steps)
### Files / modules touched               (paths with one-phrase explanations)
### Verify                                (how the next agent or human confirms it works)
```

A handoff agent must be able to read the entry **without diff** and understand: what changed conceptually, why, what user-visible behavior changed, where to look in the code, and (if breaking) the migration. If you cannot fill `Files / modules touched` and `Verify` from your task plan, you do not yet understand your own change.

Banned entry content: `Updated some files`, `Various improvements`, `Refactor`, empty subsections, merging multiple pushes into one entry.

## Conventional Commits — MUST

Every commit message uses:

```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

<body>

<footer>
```

Allowed `type`s: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `build`, `ci`, `perf`, `revert`.

- `<scope>` is a short noun for the area touched (`rules`, `installer`, `auth`, `ui`, etc.). Optional but recommended.
- `<subject>` is imperative, ≤ 72 chars, no trailing period.
- `<body>` (blank line after subject) explains **what and why**, not how.
- Breaking changes: include `BREAKING CHANGE: <description>` in the footer **and** bump `MAJOR`.

### Type → SemVer mapping (must be consistent)

| Commit type | Default bump |
|-------------|--------------|
| `feat` | `MINOR` |
| `fix`, `perf` | `PATCH` |
| `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `build`, `ci` | `PATCH` |
| Any commit with `BREAKING CHANGE:` in the footer | `MAJOR` |

If a single push contains multiple commits of mixed type, the bump matches the **highest-impact** commit in the set.

## Language

Write CHANGELOG entries and commit bodies in the **same language as the project's primary user-facing documentation** (whatever the project's introduction / overview doc is called — see `00-universal-core.mdc` "Project documentation"). Do not mix languages within an entry. If the project has no clear primary doc, default to the language of the user's most recent message in this conversation. Conventional Commits keywords (`feat`, `fix`, etc.) stay in English regardless.

## Tagging

Do **not** auto-create git tags for every patch — that would be noise. Tagging is the user's call.

## Required report (in your final message)

- `Version: <old> → <new>` and the bump category (`PATCH | MINOR | MAJOR`).
- `CHANGELOG.md`: confirm the entry is present and dated today (UTC).
- `Synced version files: <list>` (`package.json`, `Cargo.toml`, …) or `none`.
